data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work exactly as you'd expect:

```csharp
Span<nint>  signed   = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system, `nint.Size` is 8 bytes (it would be 4 on a 32-bit runtime). This feature has been available since C# 9 / .NET 5, when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced as first-class types backed by `System.IntPtr`/`System.UIntPtr`.
